<paragraph id="DD2B36F6034DC31ABED282EAFD8030D5" blockId="5.[189,528,447,473]" box="[189,528,447,473]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">
<heading id="8663819A034DC31ABED282EAFD8030D5" bold="true" box="[189,528,447,473]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" reason="3">
<emphasis id="EFE0EAE4034DC31ABED282EAFD8030D5" bold="true" box="[189,528,447,473]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">Preliminary considerations</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DD2B36F6034DC31ABED282B8FB623287" blockId="5.[187,1401,493,907]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">
The 
<typeStatus id="022F8854034DC31ABE9D82B8FEC9330B" box="[242,345,493,519]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">holotype</typeStatus>
was not examined; however, according to several caves studies and maps collected by the Association for Mexican Cave Studies (
<collectionCode id="BB85AE33034DC31ABCEA8144FD4D3327" box="[645,733,529,555]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">AMCS</collectionCode>
, information available at:http://www.mexicancaves.org/) we know that Grutas de Rancho Nuevo are the same as Grutas de 
<collectingCountry id="A5837666034DC31ABD8D8161FB173342" box="[994,1159,564,590]" name="Saint Kitts and Nevis" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">San Cristobal</collectingCountry>
; therefore, the male examined here is considered a topotype. This specimen is poorly preserved, without almost all legs, incomplete scutum and broken body. In the present work, we could only illustrate the chelicera, pedipalp, ornamentation of femur and patella IV, and male genitalia in detail. Fortunately, these structures are enough to recognize and diagnose this species. Additionally, 
<bibRefCitation id="B9054B07034DC31ABDEE8194FBBF33D7" author="Silhavy V." box="[897,1071,705,733]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 194" refId="ref6023" refString="Silhavy V. 1974. Cavernicolous opilionids from Mexico. Subterranean fauna of Mexico. Part. II. Quaderno Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei 171: 175 - 194." type="journal article" year="1974">Šilhavý (1974)</bibRefCitation>
made excellent drawings of dorsal and lateral view of the 
<typeStatus id="022F8854034DC31ABC4F81B1FD1A33F2" box="[544,650,740,766]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">holotype</typeStatus>
, which are very clear and informative for taxonomic purposes. Finally, 
<bibRefCitation id="B9054B07034DC31ABF72805DFE5D322D" author="Silhavy V." box="[285,461,775,804]" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 194" refId="ref6023" refString="Silhavy V. 1974. Cavernicolous opilionids from Mexico. Subterranean fauna of Mexico. Part. II. Quaderno Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei 171: 175 - 194." type="journal article" year="1974">Šilhavý (1974)</bibRefCitation>
, based on immature stages, mentioned two additional records for 
<taxonomicName id="1A944D75034DC31ABAD0805DFAE5322D" authorityName="Silhavy" authorityYear="1974" box="[1215,1397,775,801]" class="Arachnida" family="Stygnopsidae" genus="Troglostygnopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anophthalma">
<emphasis id="EFE0EAE4034DC31ABAD0805DFAE5322D" box="[1215,1397,775,801]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">T. anophthalma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Cueva de la Golondrina and Cueva del Nacimiento del Río San Antonio, both in Bochil, Chiapas. Due to the specificity in cave habitats in these species, it is necessary to collect adults from those caves to corroborate if they are conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="1A944D75034DC31ABCC08024FCF63287" authorityName="Silhavy" authorityYear="1974" box="[687,870,881,907]" class="Arachnida" family="Stygnopsidae" genus="Troglostygnopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anophthalma">
<emphasis id="EFE0EAE4034DC31ABCC08024FCF63287" box="[687,870,881,907]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="79">T. anophthalma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or represent undescribed species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="958E657D034DC319BED280E7FEFA3535" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="80" pageId="5" pageNumber="79" type="description">
